Application: Security Agent
  Description: Autonomous agent that patrols the app fabric for security issues, auto-remediates safe fixes, and escalates findings that require human judgment
Id: 33902654-92f7-460e-9002-64e0a5a07d16

Users authenticate with oidc
Scopes are "findings.view", "findings.triage", "findings.remediate", and "alerts.send"

A "platform engineer" has "findings.view", "findings.triage", "findings.remediate", and "alerts.send"
A "security reviewer" has "findings.view" and "findings.triage"
An "app owner" has "findings.view"

Content called "findings":
  Each finding has an app name which is text, required
  Each finding has a finding type which is one of: "iam-drift", "cve", "confidentiality-violation", "stale-secret", "state-deadlock", "error-spike"
  Each finding has a severity which is one of: "critical", "high", "medium", "low"
  Each finding has a summary which is text, required
  Each finding has details which is text
  Each finding has an affected resource which is text, required
  Each finding has a detected at which is automatic
  Each finding has a remediation action which is text
  Each finding has a remediation which is state:
    remediation starts as detected
    remediation can also be analyzing, auto-fix-applied, verified, flagged-for-human, or closed
    detected can become analyzing if the user has findings.triage
    analyzing can become auto-fix-applied if the user has findings.remediate
    analyzing can become flagged-for-human if the user has findings.triage
    auto-fix-applied can become verified if the user has findings.remediate
    auto-fix-applied can become flagged-for-human if the user has findings.triage
    verified can become closed if the user has findings.triage
    flagged-for-human can become closed if the user has findings.remediate
  Anyone with "findings.view" can view findings
  Anyone with "findings.triage" can create findings
  Anyone with "findings.remediate" can update or delete findings

Content called "scan runs":
  Each scan run has a scan type which is one of: "iam-audit", "cve-scan", "confidentiality-check", "secret-rotation-check"
  Each scan run has a started at which is automatic
  Each scan run has an apps scanned which is number
  Each scan run has a findings count which is number
  Each scan run has a status which is one of: "running", "completed", "failed"
  Anyone with "findings.view" can view scan runs
  Anyone with "findings.triage" can create or update scan runs

Channel called "security-tools":
  Direction: outbound
  Delivery: reliable

  Action called "restrict-policy":
    Takes role which is text, policy which is text
    Returns result which is text
    Requires "findings.remediate" to invoke

  Action called "rotate-secret":
    Takes arn which is text
    Returns confirmation which is text
    Requires "findings.remediate" to invoke

  Action called "describe-iam-policy":
    Takes role which is text
    Returns policy which is text
    Requires "findings.view" to invoke

Channel called "slack":
  Direction: bidirectional
  Delivery: realtime
  Carries findings
  Requires "alerts.send" to send

  Action called "post-message":
    Takes channel id which is text, text which is text
    Returns ok which is yes or no
    Requires "alerts.send" to invoke

Compute called "scanner":
  Transform: takes findings, produces findings
  Provider is "ai-agent"
  Identity: service
  Trigger on schedule every 1 hour
  Objective is ```
    You are a security scanning agent for the app fabric.
    Scan all deployed apps for IAM policy drift, dependency CVEs,
    confidentiality violations, and stale secrets. Create a finding
    for each issue detected. Prioritize internet-facing apps over
    internal, production over beta.
  ```
  Strategy is ```
    1. Use reflect.apps() to list all active apps
    2. For each app:
       a. Use reflect.app(name).definition to load its definition
       b. Use channel.invoke("security-tools", "describe-iam-policy") to get current policy
       c. Compare expected vs actual IAM policy
       d. Check dependency CVEs and secret rotation age
    3. Use content.create("findings", ...) for each issue found
    4. Use content.create("scan-runs", ...) to record this execution
  ```
  Preconditions are:
    `Compute.Scopes.contains("findings.triage")`
  Postconditions are:
    `After.content_query("findings").size() <= Before.content_query("findings").size() + 100`
  Anyone with "findings.remediate" can execute this
  Audit level: debug
  Anyone with "findings.remediate" can audit

Compute called "remediator":
  Transform: takes finding : findings, produces finding : findings
  Provider is "ai-agent"
  Identity: service
  Trigger on event "finding.created"
  Objective is ```
    You are a remediation agent. Attempt safe auto-remediation for
    security findings. Only act where the fix is deterministic and
    reversible. Flag for human review if judgment is needed.
  ```
  Strategy is ```
    1. Read the finding and classify:
       - iam-drift: use channel.invoke("security-tools", "restrict-policy")
         to narrow the IAM policy to expected permissions
       - stale-secret: use channel.invoke("security-tools", "rotate-secret")
         to rotate the expired credential
       - confidentiality-violation: flag for human (requires definition change)
       - cve, state-deadlock, error-spike: flag for human
    2. For auto-remediable: state.transition(finding, "auto-fix-applied")
    3. For human-required: state.transition(finding, "flagged-for-human")
  ```
  Preconditions are:
    `Compute.Scopes.contains("findings.remediate")`
  Postconditions are:
    `After.content_query("findings").filter(f, f.remediation == "detected").size() <= Before.content_query("findings").filter(f, f.remediation == "detected").size()`
  Anyone with "findings.remediate" can execute this
  Audit level: debug
  Anyone with "findings.remediate" can audit

When `finding.remediation.enters("flagged-for-human")`:
  Send finding to "slack"
  Log level: INFO

When `finding.created && finding.severity == "critical"`:
  Send finding to "slack"
  Log level: WARN

As a platform engineer, I want to see all active findings
  so that I can monitor fabric security posture:
    Show a page called "Security Dashboard"
    Display count of findings grouped by severity
    Display a table of findings with columns: app name, finding type, severity, remediation, detected at, remediation action
    Allow filtering by finding type, severity, and remediation
    This table subscribes to findings changes

As a security reviewer, I want to review flagged findings
  so that I can handle cases the agent cannot:
    Show a page called "Review Queue"
    Display a table of findings with columns: app name, finding type, severity, summary, details, remediation action
    Allow filtering by finding type and severity

As an app owner, I want to see findings for my apps
  so that I can understand my security posture:
    Show a page called "My Apps"
    Display a table of findings with columns: finding type, severity, remediation, summary, detected at
    Allow filtering by finding type and severity

Navigation bar:
  "Dashboard" links to "Security Dashboard" visible to platform engineer
  "Review" links to "Review Queue" visible to platform engineer, security reviewer
  "My Apps" links to "My Apps" visible to all

